94913fcb-4d8e-4314-b99e-e24646d5e551.text: It had been a long time since I went to San Francisco. Long enough to forget what the layout of the streets was, long enough to forget the sight of the Golden Gate Bridge, long enough to forget the details you don’t bother remembering. I thought revisiting the city might be a lot of fun since every memory I had of it was positive. I had plans to visit a friend there first, but when I got there, no one was answering the door and my friend seemed to be avoiding their phone and all of social media in general. So instead I went to the public transit system and got a B.A.R.T. card and went to my new first destination.

38388378-6f4c-4631-884a-f63ff3ac8fb1.text: This was obviously to a restaurant to get a bite to eat. It was a long flight here, after all, and, well, I got hungry. Who could blame me, right? I pulled out my phone and looked around for restaurants close by. A couple popped up that sounded good to me.

9e59af2a-a4dd-4e2d-ac68-14f344ecb4db.text:
First thing I ever do when I go to San Francisco is go to the pier. I always forget which number but I know it when I see it. It has the big clock type thing, might be a tower, might be a restaurant, who knows. I just like the view. I pulled out my phone and loaded up Pokemon Go and caught some ponyta while I made my way to the pier.

I got there and absorbed the sight of it all: the ships, the sun on the water, the salt smell, the activity and the happy tourists. It took me a little longer than expected by about half an hour but I felt like there was no rush, so I went out of my way to catch a rarer pokemon while I was in the city. But now I was there, in my favorite part of the state. The Golden Gate Bridge is nice and all, but nothing beats the smell of the water and the breeze and the general ambience of this pier. I spent plenty of time there and felt it was time to go do something productive, but as soon as I started standing up, I got the weirdest text from my friend who had been radio silent for days. It was only one word.

“Hello??????”

The way Blake and I talk is very casual and never so ominous or accusatory. The tone of this one-word text caught me so off guard, I fumbled my phone and it fell off the pier. Not into the water, thank god, but down to where people generally don’t go. I was not going to lose my phone though. I went after it. Jumped right over the barrier and dropped about 10 feet to the ground below. That’s when it hit me.

No idea what it was but it hit me hard, right in the back, knocking all the air out of my lungs. I couldn’t breath for a second but whatever hit me could. It grabbed the side of my head and slammed it against the concrete wall to my left and my vision went blurry. I dropped to my knees and my attacker held me up and prevented me from curling up on the ground. I made out a figure entering my limited vision but couldn’t make out many details. Just a red hoodie, really. He pulled my face close to his and the next detail that made itself clear was the strong smell of blood near his face. He chuckled and threw me to the ground and the last thing I saw were his hands getting closer and closer to my eyes. Then I couldn’t see anything. I could still feel though, and that was the problem. I felt his fingers dig into my eye sockets. I felt the indescribable pain of having my eyes pulled out of my head. I tried to scream for help, but he put his other hand over my throat and pushed just hard enough to make breathing impossible. I would describe the sound, but with all the pain I felt, sound was muted, or muffled at least. My only working sense was the pain I was in.

He loosened up on my neck for about a second and I felt hope fill my lungs. Then I felt a shoe on my neck where his hand had been. Then I felt nothing at all.

a3a1da79-790b-4d4e-b492-166e26c12e15.text:
Mcdonalds is consistent, if nothing else. I know I can get a meal I’ve had before and wifi I need now. I got off at the stop my gps indicated. I thought I saw a couple of people on the subway give me a look, not a malicious one but more of an uncomfortable one. Maybe it wasn’t directed at me but still it’s the very idea of judgement that kind of annoyed me. I mean Mcdonalds isn’t so bad is it? Also they couldn’t have known I was going there. I was so in my head about the look they may or may not have given me I didn’t notice where I was going until someone pushed past me and I realized i was standing still at the top of the escalator. I felt my face go red and walked quickly where the gps told me to go. I put my headphones in to try to mask my shame and avoided eye contact. As I walked out, I heard the high pitched scream of the subway rolling out.

I went to the Mcdonalds and ordered what I normally get: a number 6 (10 nuggets and a bunch of fries). Not delicious but not the worst food in the world. Better than going hungry, I guess. I connected to the wifi and tried calling my friend again. While it was ringing, I looked out the window to my

2004d61e-de1c-4a3c-b69f-2b991b4f2c78.text:
I saw someone walk by the window in a hoodie that looked a lot like my own, but it seemed to have a yellow glow to it.  I looked at my own hoodie and made sure it was as white as I remembered it being, and sure enough, it was. I looked back up and they glanced over at me. I couldn’t make out their facial features as well as I should, but their gaze carried a swift and empowering energy, not one I ever felt before. They looked down at the phone in their hands and seemed concerned.  Another look my way, another shot of energy, then they looked away to the street. Seeing as it was all clear, they crossed. Their golden hoodie moved with their motions, but seemed to flow not as a normal hoodie would. Must have been made with expensive silk or something. Eventually the stranger was out of sight and at that second my friend’s voicemail message rang out through my headphones. I gathered myself and spoke into the phone. “Hey Blake, uhh, hi yeah it’s me. You have my contact saved but I have no idea what name you have me under. Last you told me I was called ‘Stooge Number 54’, so yeah 54 calling. Just call me back when you get this. I’m here, in San Francisco and ready to meet; just hit me up.”

I hung up my phone and finished the rest of my food. As I did, I checked out the window for that gilded stranger in the hoodie that was like mine. No sign of them. I did see someone across the street, though, in a hoodie that looked like it was coated in ketchup. That made me nauseous, honestly. What a crazy city. Anybody who was walking around in public smelling like ketchup must have lost a bet or something. But enough standing around staring at people in hoodies, I needed to do the next thing on my checklist.

5c5ae23e-29d2-4143-bc7b-d0d7c328f606.text:
I saw someone walk by the window in a hoodie that looked a lot like my own, but red. I looked at my own hoodie and made sure it was as white as I remembered it, and sure enough, it was. I looked back up and he was staring at the window. No, he was staring at me. I couldn’t make out his face very well but his gaze carried an palpable energy, not one I ever felt. He started walking again but in a less casual way...more of a shambling way. He didn’t break eye contact. His red hoodie moved with his motions, but stiffly and it seemed to crack with his movements. I felt paralyzed. Eventually he was out of sight and at that second my friend’s voicemail message rang out through my headphones. I gathered myself and spoke into the phone. “Hey Blake, uhh, hi yeah it’s me. You have my contact saved but I have no idea what name you have me under. Just call me back when you get this. I’m here, in San Francisco and ready to meet; just hit me up.”

I hung up and threw out the rest of my food. I had lost my appetite. As I did, I checked out the window for that super creepy guy in the hoodie that was like mine but red. No sign of him. I did see someone across the street though in a hoodie that looked like it was glowing. That made me smile honestly, what a great idea it was. A hoodie that glows in the dark must have countless benefits. But enough standing around staring at people in hoodies, I needed to do the next thing on my checklist.

4c2be9c0-9526-4a5b-abf8-b6b559c6ad33.text: I figured my first course of action should probably be grab a hotel since my friend had gone radio silent. I pulled out my phone and looked around for a place to stay, checking hotel sites, Airbnb, and just the map in general. I found a place for a low enough price and set it as my destination.

6d1d78d9-f450-413d-95c5-747e2e32b36d.text: I booked an Airbnb. I planned on living in a house and a little ghosting wasn’t going to stop me. I got the address and saved it to my notes for faster access. Before I headed over, though, I thought I might as well make the most of the daylight and do something. The next place I started looking for was…

efcd28d5-baa2-4c4d-9256-b200d08eb477.text: I booked a hotel. Vacation living isn’t complete without a hotel stay, after all. Plus the one I booked had a breakfast included if I got up at ungodly hours, so there was a plus. I didn’t plan on heading over for several hours though, so in the meantime, I....

ce0179f8-2370-450d-82fd-f4dab62b7a0f.text: I booked a motel. I didn’t plan on spending too much and in the city, everything is expensive. This little place was a few miles away from the city, but still easily accessible so getting there and back wouldn’t be a problem. I was in no rush to get there though so I checked around on my phone for…

e3f912b1-8b24-4687-a7cb-75617ee8ed6b.text: There was a Denny’s near the next exit, so I decided to go there. I tapped it and got the directions vaguely memorized and felt eyes staring at me. There was no one in front of me and no one right next to me. There were only two other people in this car at all, a woman far away and a guy two seats down from me. She was on her phone and he was staring straight ahead at the window. I looked straight forward, too, and saw his eyes glaring at mine in the reflection. I froze. I couldn’t look away, and I tried. It was like he was pulling my attention from the window into his eyes. I didn’t want to know what would happen if I looked into his eyes directly. The subway car slowed and the woman gathered her things and stood next to the door. The man broke the indirect eye contact and I felt his gaze shoot directly through me.

aef320d8-f287-4de9-bd21-230af07b1f6b.text:
I looked back at him and met his empty stare. His eyes looked like they used to be someone’s, but never his own. I don't know how else to describe those eyes. He was giving me a vacant stare, holding his head sideways. When the subway finally stopped, he broke into a grin. It wasn’t a grin formed by positivity or humor, though, I don’t know how, but he made sure I knew it was a grin of malice. The doors opened and the woman stepped out. Without breaking eye contact, the man stood up and shambled out of the car and grinned wider and wider at me. I followed. It felt right.

After he saw me get up, his head rolled back and he cackled, loud and echoing in the empty underground. This made me chuckle. Whatever was happening, wherever he was leading me, I knew it wasn’t something that would happen above ground. It couldn’t, with the way he was walking, or attempting to walk, rather. It looked like he didn’t have full control over his legs, or maybe like he wasn’t so ready to use them. Maybe they were just asleep after being on the subway for so long? I didn’t care. I just followed him. I couldn't resist. His gaze, his looking into my eyes had the same effect on me as did the Piper's flute in Hamlin. He continued following the woman. Eventually, she turned a corner, and he got on all fours and chased her. Took off, quieter than fog. I ran to catch up and found him already over her. She was done. I couldn’t have saved her if I wanted to. The man already ripped her throat out and was starting to tear the rest of her apart. The kill was so fast and silent I didn’t know what even happened until he grabbed something from inside her and threw it at me. He looked at me and said the only thing I ever heard him say. In a raspy voice he said, “Hungry?”

I dropped to my knees and picked up whatever it was he threw and sank my own teeth into it. It tasted the way scratching an itch felt, like remembering the name of a song you only heard once but loved, like the concept of satisfaction. I wanted more, I needed more. I reached down to grab something else but he lunged at my hands. It was clear this was his meal now, what he gave me was only a sample. He grabbed me by my shoulder and jerked me towards him and put his other hand on my ear. For a hand that had been covered in blood, it was unusually cold, almost icy, sending a shiver down my spine. But something else was giving me the chills. It was footsteps. The man looked over my shoulder and I turned to look, too. Someone was walking toward where we came from, walking toward the subway. The man nodded at me and shoved me backwards a little. I understood. I got up and stalked down them down. When I was close enough, I jumped onto their back and did it. I hunted down my first meal. I ate until I couldn’t anymore. I figured there was no reason to go to Denny’s now. Not that I could anyway. My hoodie was covered in blood. I thought, probably shouldn’t stay out very long looking like this and considered what to do next.

467b8370-ab19-4008-80aa-35192333d30a.text: I can’t go to an Airbnb looking like this, but there aren’t many places I could go looking like this, really. I settled on a hotel. What, are they gonna say no when I hand over the money? So now I have a place to stay and a taste for blood. What else is there to do but go to the pier? San Francisco is a big  city, I doubt anyone will even notice me.

a806de1c-f7a7-42ec-9a19-59afe3aca175.text: I can’t go to an Airbnb looking like this. I couldn't go ANYWHERE looking like this. I settled on a small motel outside the city. Plenty of bloodstained people probably go to motels anyway right? I’ll blend in.  So now I have a place to stay and a taste for blood. What else is there to do but go to the pier? San Francisco is a big city, I doubt anyone will even notice me.

6a07e7ea-145b-4a93-8b46-5c9727b4a4ae.text: I avoided his stare and instead, looked at the woman about to get off. The man turned his head, not fully backwards but more than a normal head should turn for sure. He stared her down as well. She felt it, I could tell by her sudden stiffness. The man between us had to have sensed our nervousness. It would be hard to miss.The subway began to slow down. He started to turn his head back towards me and I could make out a smile in my peripheral vision. It wasn’t exactly right though, slightly bigger than a smile should be. It felt like he was doing it for for me, or for me and the woman. The subway slowed down. There was no happiness in the smile, but there was a smell. The subway slowed. The smell was familiar. It was one of blood. The subway stopped and the doors opened. I jumped at the sudden noise and realized I hadn’t been breathing. I turned to look at the woman and just saw her get off. The man followed. I had no options, I had to follow. I had to

ec26f8b9-f155-4e46-83ec-661f9765d7a0.text:
He saw me get up and grinned, somehow wider than before. This one showed off three rows of teeth. It was a dare of a grin. A challenge. I took it and followed him. He followed her. She started to walk faster and he matched her pace. I hurried to keep up. Eventually she rounded a corner and he dropped to all fours and chased her down. I ran and saw I was too late. He had already slaughtered her. He was holding her throat in his mouth. I was in shock; he just ate...loud smacking with no worry of being caught or any regard for hiding what he was doing. He looked up and saw me. He saw my revulsion, my objection to his actions. He saw and understood I would not be dining with him today. He saw me and he screamed, it was deafening and made my knees buckle and give out. I curled on the ground covering my ears trying to block out the sound he was making. I couldn’t run. The screech was only stopped by what I can only imagine were footsteps. I couldn’t hear anything, just the ringing of the deafening noise still in my ears. I looked up and saw a familiar face ending the screaming man from the subway’s shrieks. I barely choked out one word. “Blake?”

“Hey sorry I couldn’t answer your calls and texts. I was a little busy hunting this clown down. Hard to kill, but someone needs to do it. Takes a special kind of blade, like this one, here.” Blake handed me a golden switchblade. “That will do the trick. Took a lot of trial and error to figure it out, I won’t lie. So where are you headed next?” I opened my mouth but no words could come out. My hands were shaking holding the knife. “Yeah, I should’ve figured. Hey, no worries. Just meet me at my place whenever you feel able, deal? See you then.” And with that, Blake walked off in the direction I had come from.

I gathered myself and looked around.  I had to figure out what my next course of action would be. No way I was going to Denny’s. I had lost my appetite.

93e321af-c28a-41a1-81ce-9bedc1bbf88b.text:
I got up shakily and tip-toed over to the mess of a body. She was, and I mean this in the most sympathetic way, eviscerated. Her murder was brutal and instant. I couldn’t bear to look any more. I turned toward the man who did this and was almost equally horrified. The man who did it was not a man. Maybe he never was, or maybe he wasn’t one anymore, but whatever the case was, there was only one human killed here tonight. Blake had stabbed the creature in the side, where most people would have ribs, only the mark it left was as if he didn’t use a gold blade but rather a grenade. The surrounding skin was charred and cracked, nothing like what a normal knife would do. I didn’t give the option to touch the mangled mess a second thought, there were way too many things that could go wrong. Eventually I looked at the thing’s face. There were eyes there sure, but not eyes it had for long. They were stolen from someone at some point. It was hard to tell how I knew that, but it was a truth you could just see. I was one more observation away from throwing up so I just left. I couldn’t be alone anymore, I had to go somewhere or to someone. I followed  Blake.

I was sure I was, at least. I didn’t see anyone or hear anything, not even the subways. Until a marimba shattered the silence, making me jump out of my skin. There was a phone ringing in front of me. I could see the glow of the screen from the ground in front of me, and the glow revealed a person farther down. I couldn’t tell much from the dim light provided, but his walking style was exactly like I saw earlier. The same shambling walk, the same inhuman rhythm. There was another one. I felt for the knife Blake gave me and found it in my pocket, but this monster wasn’t walking towards me. He was headed for the stairs up and out of the subway. As he ascended, he pulled up his blood stained hood. Then he was gone. How many monsters like this were in the city? And if they don’t just stay underground, how have they continued killing like they do? My heart was racing and my mind was full of questions. The marimba ringtone focused me and gave me a way forward. I looked for the phone and any courage I had was taken from me one last time. It was Blake’s phone. The blood on the monster who got away must have been fresh. The body before me must have been Blake, or at least what was left. I grabbed the phone and looked at the caller ID. Someone with a private number was calling. I didn’t know what to do besides let it ring out. They didn’t bother to leave a voicemail. When I pressed the home button, the phone scanned my fingerprint and unlocked. I don’t remember ever setting it or ever having this phone with me at any point, though. It seemed appropriate to do some snooping, maybe find an answer.

c32c2d9b-8c1c-4339-ad1a-8006d878dd6b.text: I opened Snapchat almost instinctively. To my surprise, there weren’t many people Blake talked to, and even the people who had been sent anything hadn’t opened any of them. I checked the map part of it where it tracks any friends and saw the Bitmoji Blake made, a pirate with an attitude, but I also saw my own Bitmoji. He was at a McDonald’s not too far from here, I could walk there in a couple of minutes. I also saw my own Bitmoji though, walking in that direction and in a different hoodie. That was the only difference: the one walking had a red hoodie and the one at McDonald’s had a white one. That meant there were three of me in San Francisco right now, or maybe more depending on who wasn’t on the map right now. I don’t know how it was possible, but apparently it was. I closed out of Snapchat, not too happy with what I found.

f072f69b-0337-4f4a-bb88-0ca1afa53403.text: Blake still didn’t have an Instagram account that I knew of, but the app was installed. I opened it up and saw the sign in page. Whatever the app was downloaded for, it wasn’t in use anymore. I closed out of Instagram.

ed33b909-0e98-4eef-8d60-a36ad078199e.text: I opened up the messages and saw a lot of names and numbers I didn’t recognize. Dozens of different area codes and short conversations. Some were spam texts, but Blake had replied with numbers that triggered the spam bots into different codes. None made any sense to me, though. The latest conversation has a Georgia area code and only said one thing: “B.A.R.T.” It all seemed very ominous and dangerous, especially after seeing what happened to Blake and that Girl from the subway. I closed out of the messages, I didn’t want to see more.

4a2d3490-0e38-428d-8b82-43cb6117d4e5.text:
I opened up the notes app, hoping some clarity would come of it. After I read a couple of them it felt like a mistake. Blake had laid out all the research and hunts and explanations of what was going on with these creatures. I don’t know if they were meant to be read as they were; they felt more like notes than a story, but I read them anyway. One part that stuck out was something like an interview Blake had with one of the monsters, but only a couple questions went answered, anyway. This monster seemed to be very uncooperative. Blake asked why they were doing this. Why all the senseless killing, why the brutal murders. Apparently the monster just grunted out the word “hungry.”

Blake also didn’t refer to them as monsters under the thinking that would make them the enemy or that fear fed into their power or their hunger. Blake simply referred to them as Vacks. There was no explanation for it, but the term Vack kept coming up.

919a1901-1b1f-482d-840d-9470c40db13d.text: So what I learned from Blake’s phone is there are monsters in the city, they’re called Vacks, other people know about them and hunt them, and they’re hungry or just empty inside so they prey on other people to fill that void. There are also at least two other versions of me in San Francisco and one of them is wearing red, I think. Unsettling, sure, but there was a Vack who killed Blake, so there was at least one I could go after. I had a lead to follow.

3518653a-49cc-466b-8622-4f793ffe60ed.text:
I put my phone and Blake’s phone in my pocket and left the underground into the all too bright city. I didn’t realize how long I had been down there until I had to close my eyes in the daylight. I saw an ad for the McDonald’s in one direction and walked that way for about a minute. The streets were crowded. I focused my attention on whatever was directly in front of me and let the rest fade to obscurity. If there were more Vacks out here, I didn’t care. I was focused on finding myself and warning me about what was happening. At least, that was my intent. I crossed my own path before I even reached the McDonald’s, but it wasn’t me. At least, not anymore. The hoodie that version of me wore was red, seemingly stained that way. That version of me didn’t walk right, it was that same gut wrenching shamble I saw below ground. That version of me was a Vack. That me was the Vack that killed Blake. That me was staring into the building next to it. It was the McDonald’s where I was. I was looking at me looking at me. Or, no, I wasn’t looking at me. This was not a human anymore, this is a Vack, a predator, a monster. My focus on him was shifted when the marimba rang out again. Blake’s phone was getting another call, but this time, not from some random number. It showed the name “Vinn Jillette” and the picture was me, poorly photoshopped on a magician. I guess this is how Blake saved my contact. Only, I wasn’t calling anyone right now. I checked my phone and didn’t see anything. I looked up for the Vack to see if it was making any calls but it had shambled out of sight. There was only one other me that could be making a call at that moment, so i walked over to the McDonald’s to check on myself.

I saw me again. Not a me like the one that turned into a Vack, but not a me that knew so much, either. The worrisome part was that me was holding a phone, my phone, to his ear. I looked at Blake’s phone, ringing, then looked at myself, calling. I couldn’t answer. What would I say? Also, I would see me answer from the McDonald’s and what would I think? I couldn’t answer. Not yet, at least. I needed more answers. I looked across the street and crossed when it was clear. If the Vack was me at any point, I knew he would probably go to the pier sooner or later. I planned on catching it there, before it made any more carcasses.

8306d09e-cfa9-45ea-a809-edd56f6fcbf5.text: Seems like you did a speedrun of my game. Try not going to the pier so soon if you decide to play again. Get a meal first or a room. Live a little. There will probably be another opportunity to die later; go have fun in the city try again.

ee1ae2bb-c9cd-4ec9-b62d-8bf2067962a1.text: It had been a long time since I went to San Francisco. Long enough to forget what the layout of the streets was, long enough to forget the sight of the Golden Gate Bridge, long enough to forget the details you don’t bother remembering. I thought revisiting the city might be a lot of fun since every memory I had of it was positive. I had plans to visit a friend there first, but when I got there, no one was answering the door and my friend seemed to be avoiding their phone and all of social media in general. So instead I went to the public transit system and got a B.A.R.T. card and went to my new first destination.

7ea64b4f-ff7b-49c2-96a5-543dd9e0d4f8.text: You just died here, do something else.

f9bc0bd4-59c0-4d4d-9988-5e181714cb87.text: I figured my next course of action should probably grab a hotel since my friend has gone radio silent. I pulled out my phone and looked around for a place to stay, checking hotel sites, Airbnb, and just the map in general. I found a place for a low enough price and set it as my destination.

49833748-34e2-4a6f-abbc-ab623388bd4f.text:
I left the subway system and made a beeline for the pier. I didn’t know what I planned on finding but I was definitely going to find it there. As I made my way over, I did a quick assessment of what I knew. Firstly, I had killed someone. That was obvious enough. I also knew it felt good, though, satisfying. I also knew I didn’t use to feel like this, as much as an hour ago I would never have dreamt of doing this. Killing and eating people was not something on my bucket list. But here I was, ready to do it again. Excited almost. Anxious to find my next victim. Something must have happened to me between then and now. Maybe it was like werewolf rules with that guy on the subway? Though he didn’t bite me or anything. The why didn’t matter to me. The how hardly mattered to me. All I could think about was when and where my next meal would be.

My stomach was still full of that person in the subway, but I was still so hungry. Hungry enough to make my vision fog up. Maybe it was real fog in the city, though? No, something was wrong with my sight. Everything around my peripherals was blurring and everything in focus was becoming doubled. My eyes weren’t working as well as they used to. So my destination finally had a reason. I needed new eyes. I made my way over to the pier somehow as my sight got worse and worse.

affbbdff-6a50-4138-8a7f-9a39cc4208c9.text: I tried to find where people would be suitable to pounce on and attack, but no such opportunity presented itself in my limited eyesight. My only idea was to jump down to the shore and get under the pier and see if anyone was isolated there.

9a9f3640-a295-49de-9ce0-4cf99f31e8a2.text: I booked an Airbnb. I planned on living in a house and a little ghosting wasn’t going to stop me. I got the address and saved it to my notes for faster access. Before I headed over though, I thought I might as well make the most of the daylight and do something. The next place I went had to be the pier

c7b3389b-dd92-4286-bde5-c6f7ff29d933.text: I booked a hotel. Vacation living isn’t complete without a hotel stay, after all. Plus the one I booked had a breakfast included if I got up at ungodly hours, so there was a plus. I didn’t plan on heading over for several hours though, so in the meantime I headed for the pier

6af8fa7c-73ad-47b9-a258-565a77c7a028.text: I booked a motel. I didn’t plan on spending too much and in the city, everything is expensive. This little place was a few miles away from the city but still easily accessible, so getting there and back wouldn’t be a problem. I was in no rush to get there, though, so I checked around on my phone for directions to the pier.

0bc28b6e-16c6-4a1b-9629-f3e64623ff05.text: I sniffed around, but the smell of the water and the restaurants and the people all around me struck any chance of finding someone near me. I did notice though my smell was much keener than before, almost as if I had a smell version of a telescope. Like a smelloscope. Strange. Useless at the moment, though.

f5797fc7-0daf-43a3-9aed-00e11bf8bcd3.text: I listened for footsteps but that wasn’t helpful at all. There were footsteps all around me, this was a city, this pier is pretty popular; if there were footsteps near me, I couldn’t tell. I did notice my sense of hearing seemed much sharper than before. Like I could pick out exactly how many people were walking above me at once. Strange. Useless at the moment, though.

3986b51c-f6ab-4d46-9cb8-c2ce3e1ebe50.text: I listened carefully this time, but the sound of the water and the music and the people all around me struck any chance of finding someone near me. I did notice, though, my hearing was much keener than before, almost as if I had a sound version of a telescope. Like a soundescope. Or a telesound? This is getting me nowhere.

a86b6453-cd3d-4a33-8d11-5ab56819dcc1.text: I smelled for footsteps but that wasn’t helpful at all. Footsteps aren’t something that can even be smelled. I felt kind of ridiculous for even trying that. I did notice my sense of smell seemed much sharper than before. Like I could pick out exactly which people hadn’t showered that day. This is getting me nowhere.

1a125af6-aacd-426c-9d0b-b220de29877c.text: Instinct brought me here and it was instinct to wait here. So that’s what I did. Then I heard one set of footsteps walk right above me and heard the unmistakable sound of a dropped phone. When it hit the ground near me I felt the vibration it made through my feet. I waited seconds more. Bait never fell so easily into my hands. I heard the person jump the barrier that kept people from falling off the pier, I felt the person land in front of me, and with my limited vision, I saw their back was turned to me. It was my time to strike. I punched their back with a force I hadn’t felt before. The person before me started to crumple. I grabbed their head and slammed it against the wall a couple of times before walking in front of them. I pulled them up to my face by their throat and took a deep sniff. I could smell a lot about them from that. Most importantly, I could smell a good pair of working eyes. I threw the person to the ground and held them there while i did what I had to do. First I pulled out my own eyes, which is hard to do when you’ve never done it before. I threw them aside and reached for my new set which I just had to remove from their old owner. I popped them into my head where my eyes used to be and blinked a couple of times. Then my vision came back. I stood up and crushed the neck of my next meal under my foot. I didn’t need anyone screaming or anything. I dragged him further under the pier and began to feast again.

1d74204f-9ed9-4b4a-8b5a-dbcde8dc9f4f.text:
I looked around with my new and useful eyes. Everything was sharper and more in focus, even my peripherals. It was like putting on glasses for the first time, it was like I could look everywhere at once. It was as though I had some kind of telescope for my eyes. Which I guess would just be a telescope, but it felt clearer. I also noticed how I could feel every inch of my body, inside and out, and process every sensation all at once. I could feel the ground below me, feel every inch of skin on my body, feel the blood rushing through my veins and down my throat. I could tell which blood was mine and which blood was not. The taste of it was also enhanced, like the flavor wasn’t as important as determining what it was that my tongue was tasting. I could taste the blood type of the person I just ate. Type A positive. All my senses seemed heightened, my smell, sight, touch, sound, and taste, they all seemed more focused on everything around me instead of one thing specifically. They were so focused, I could tell when someone was running above the ground on the pier. I listened close to where they stopped and heard typing sounds like a text. Then I felt the phone my victim dropped vibrate on the ground a few yards from me. I quietly crawled over there silent enough so I couldn’t even hear it. I looked at the phone and it had one new notification. A text message from my own phone. I saved my contact as “Idiot supreme” so I’d kind of recognize it anywhere. The text consisted of one sentence.

“Go to the Bridge.”

1d5fcd3b-d9c4-48a9-94ff-daed4f9593ff.text:
I took a quick account of what happened since I saw the guy on the subway. So first, I saw that guy kill someone, then I killed someone, then ate them, then killed someone else and ate them, too. Something pretty bad happened to me. This felt like it couldn't be real. I hoped it was.

I couldn’t explain much, but I did get the sense of knowing truths. Unexplainable but undeniable facts that implanted themselves in my head. One was the police wouldn’t be a concern. I don’t know how I knew, but I did. This played into the other truth: that there are more out there like me, and I create more like me. This truth seemed explainable enough, though. Since I already saw someone like me kill someone else, but the second half of the truth is what bugged me. If I create them, do they not exist until then? I existed for years until I really existed in the way I do now. Maybe it has something to do with these new eyes, the subway guy had off eyes and noticing that was the first step in living up to what I’ve become. Something about that conclusion didn’t feel right though, like I was missing a key part. I decided to not worry about it then and to shift my attention to something else.

66b25b05-fa99-43ac-b13a-d885bf3ffbe1.text:
I made my way to the pier. On my walk there, I thought I saw the Vack that killed Blake. I pulled out Blake’s phone and texted my own number, hoping it would pop up on the phone the Vack had so I could verify it without getting closer. I just sent one word to me.

“Hello?”

If the Vack did get it, it was enough to show someone out there knew about the murder in the subway by using the phone that was discarded by it. If some other phone got the text, it was simple enough to pass as something Blake would say after being so silent for so long.

The Vack didn’t look one way or another. It didn’t even notice any text. Then it slipped out of my sight into the crowd of people on the pier.

I didn’t remember the specific name, but I knew the one. It was lodged in my memory from my last visit and before that even. This pier was of significance in some way or another. I crossed the last road separating me from my destination and saw me again. It was no me that I had seen before though, this one was wearing a grey hoodie. I looked at my own hoodie and noticed for the first time it was glowing gold where the knife Blake gave me was. The me in the McDonald’s had a white hoodie so it couldn’t be him. Was there a fourth me? He surprised me so much I missed  my opportunity to cross the road and heavy traffic started up again. Between cars, I saw the grey me look over the pier. A bus passed and then that me was gone. I could only assume where he went but no way was I going to follow under the pier. Not after what I saw in the subway. I waited impatiently for the light to go red again so I could cross and sprinted to the pier.

A brief look around revealed no one. Or at least, no me. I was the only me I saw. I pulled out my own phone and texted myself. Maybe the Vack would see this one.

“Go to the Bridge.”

154e7e03-7194-4178-8655-8e94c1fc7059.text:
After booking a place to stay, I headed toward the pier. First thing I ever do when I go to San Francisco is go to the pier. I always forget which number it is, but I know it when I see it. It has the big clock type thing, might be a tower, might be a restaurant, who knows? I just like the view. I pull out my phone and load up Pokemon Go and catch some ponyta while I make my way over there.

I got there and took in the sight of it all. Now I was here, in my favorite part of the state. Sure I’ve seen the redwoods and Disney, but nothing beats this pier. I don’t know exactly what it is about it that makes it so nice. Could be the smell of the water and the breeze and the general ambiance, but whatever it is, it really is the best. While I was there, I got a text from myself, which was a little weird 'cause I thought I couldn’t do that but hey, weirder things happen I guess. All it said was “Go to the Bridge.” But hey, not a bad idea, I’ve got time to kill.

2e58c0f7-a253-420e-920e-126c21e95d41.text:
I left the McDonald’s and headed toward the pier. First thing I ever do when I go to San Francisco is go to the pier. I always forget which number it is but I know it when I see it. It has the big clock type thing, might be a tower, might be a restaurant, who knows. I just like the view. I pull out my phone and load up Pokemon Go and catch some ponyta while I make my way over there.

I get there and take in the sight of it all. Now I was here, in my favorite part of the state. Sure I’ve seen the redwoods and Disney, but nothing beats this pier. I don’t know exactly what it is about it that makes it so nice. Could be the smell of the water and the breeze and the general ambience, but whatever it is, it really is the best. I go into the clock building and take a look around. There are all sorts of goings on here, rich dudes in suits, less rich dudes in collared shirts, someone obviously from the south with how they’re dressed. A real melting pot of people. While I was there, I got a text from myself, which was a little weird 'cause I thought I couldn’t do that but hey, weirder things happen, I guess. All it said was “Go to the Bridge.” Not a bad idea, I had time to kill. I started to leave the clock building but out of the corner of my eye I saw him again, the guy in the red looking hoodie. He was climbing up the wall from under the pier and just the sight of him drained every positive emotion the pier brought to me. The red on his hoodie seemed to drip to parts that weren’t as red before and it dawned on me that it could be blood. The feeling from the McDonald’s came back but it was more definable this time. It was a lack of feeling. The sight of him made me devoid of any emotion and was like a vacuum to feeling. I wanted to avoid him. I hurried to the bridge.

968234b7-6e53-483f-83b4-1b9eb9b9a321.text:
I left the McDonald’s and headed toward the pier. First thing I ever do when I go to San Francisco is go to the pier. I always forget which number it is but I know it when I see it. It has the big clock type thing, might be a tower, might be a restaurant, who knows. I just like the view. I pull out my phone and load up Pokemon Go and catch some ponyta while I make my way over there.

I get there and take in the sight of it all. Now I was here, in my favorite part of the state. Sure I’ve seen the redwoods and Disney, but nothing beats this pier. I don’t know exactly what it is about it that makes it so nice. Could be the smell of the water and the breeze and the general ambience but whatever it is, it really is the best. I go into the clock building and take a look around. There’s all sorts of goings on in here, rich dudes in suits, less rich dudes in collared shirts, someone obviously from the south with how they’re dressed. A real melting pot of people. While I was there, I got a text from myself, which was a little weird 'cause I thought I couldn’t do that but hey, weirder things happen, I guess. All it said was “Go to the Bridge.” Not a bad idea, I’ve got time to kill. I turned to leave the clock building and saw the glowing hoodie person again. Their back was to me but the shine was unmistakable. I got that same feeling of hope, or valor or virtue or something, I couldn't quite place it yet, but it filled every ounce of me. I tried walking over to them but before I could, they were gone in the crowd. Shame. Oh well.

b82a32a7-8853-4770-8042-eaa85fcda27a.text:
I got to the bridge after a long walk. The sun was starting to get low at this point, but I wasn’t too eager to get to where I was staying right now; I had a mystery text to solve. I figured I wouldn’t find any answers in traffic on the bridge so I went to the park near it. The park seemed oddly empty though, almost no one around. There was that person in the glowing hoodie though, at the far end. There was also the creep in the red hoodie, barely visible to me. It looked like the gold hoodie person was ready to fight, though. I moved closer to get a better look.

I wish I didn’t. After getting closer the red hoodie guy lunged toward the gold hoodie person and took them both down. I walked closer still and regretted it more. The person in the gold hoodie looked like me. Not in a looks like my brother way but looked exactly like me. The same could be said about the guy in the red hoodie. Both of them were dead though. The gold me had his throat torn open. The red me had a knife in his side which sent cracks all along that half of his body. It was hard to look at the scene. I didn’t know how there became so many of me but somehow there was and someone texted me this and wanted me to see it. I’ve had enough of mysteries. I'm going to sleep. I’m going to leave San Francisco.

d90de10c-b8fb-4c0e-b7d2-3cf6f7e96235.text:
I got to the bridge after a long walk. The sun was starting to get low at this point but I wasn’t worried about night right now, I had a mystery text to solve. I figured I wouldn’t find any answers in traffic on the bridge so I went to the park near it. The park seemed oddly empty though, almost no one around. There was that person in the glowing hoodie though, at the far end. There was also the guy in the ketchup hoodie, barely visible to me. It looked like the gold hoodie person was ready to fight, though. I moved closer to get a better look.

As I approached the gold hoodie person saw me and ran my way. After them ran the red hoodie guy, but on all fours and unnaturally fast. I wanted to shout something like look out or any kind of warning, but the sight of the red hoodie man was choking me. When the person in gold caught up to me, two things happened. The first was I recognized them as myself, but less selfish. I don’t know how I could tell from a glance, but it was evident in his demeanor. The second thing that happened was the red hoodie man stopped and was recognized as myself, as well. There was no feeling in the red hoodie version of myself. Gold me pulled a gold knife and red me stood in an attack stance. I looked between the two of them and made the decision of which to help.

dd7ec0b1-b284-4df9-b060-810677352ab6.text:
I got to the bridge after a long walk. The sun was starting to get low at this point but I wasn’t worried about night right now, I had a mystery text to solve. I figured I wouldn’t find any answers in traffic on the bridge so I went to the park near it. The park seemed oddly empty though, almost no one around. There was that person in the glowing hoodie though, at the far end. There was also the guy in the ketchup hoodie, barely visible to me. It looked like the gold hoodie person was ready to fight though. I moved closer to get a better look.

As I approached the red hoodie guy saw me and looked my way. Even from as far away as I was I felt the extreme energy filling me. It wasn’t so much of the energy you get from caffeine or anything but more of the energy you get when you hear a knock at your door and aren’t expecting someone. It was the energy you get when you’re in bed and feel someone looking at you. It’s the self defense energy, but twisted into an energy I could use as an attack. I looked closely at the red hoodie guy and saw my own face in the hood. It was off, but only by a bit.

I looked back to the gold hoodie person. I didn’t have to look too hard to see they were me, too. The red me got closer and closer to the gold me. I had to make a decision of which one to help.

4c906354-448c-4670-9e49-d022fa2ae473.text:
I locked eyes with the red hoodie version of me and saw his bloodstained features. Everything from his face to his hands had that red tint and he radiated the smell of it. He made my decision easy. I sucker punched the gold hoodie me and that's when red pounced on him. The knife flew from the gold one’s hands and  into the grass a few feet away while the red hoodie me tore out the throat of the gold hoodie me. He then messily dissected the corpse and started feasting at a surprising speed. I watched in morbid fascination until he tossed a chunk to me and said the first word I ever heard him say.

“Hungry?”

ac0e98a8-2576-4438-98e5-0c79dcd03f2c.text:
I locked eyes with the gold hoodie version of me and saw the fearlessness in his eyes. He radiated a calm and reassuring energy that felt promising. He made my decision easy.  He tossed me his knife and decked the red hoodie monster. The two of them started brawling, fists flying and I’m pretty sure I saw some teeth gnashing in there too. Eventually, the red one pinned the gold one to the ground and the gold one shouted the first thing I heard him say.

“Now!”

I jumped forward and thrust the knife into the red one’s hoodie. It sank in like a hot knife through butter, but I don’t know if it was because of the sharpness of the knife or because of the place I stabbed or what. Then a bright gold light emanated from the wound and the red monster stopped moving entirely. I sat back on the grass, pushing the body away from me while the gold me sat next to me and sighed. Neither of us spoke for several minutes. Then he said “I guess you have questions right?”

887ae6e8-5f44-49a2-bf66-2ab94430b218.text:
I locked eyes with the gold hoodie version of me and saw the fearlessness in his eyes. He radiated a calm and reassuring energy that felt promising. He made my decision easy.  I looked toward the red hoodie guy just behind him as a warning from afar. The gold one turned just in time to deck the red one in the jaw. I began running over. The two of them started brawling, fists flying and I’m pretty sure I saw some teeth gnashing in there, too. Eventually, the gold one pinned the red one to the ground and the gold one shouted the first thing I heard him say.

“Do it!”

I looked around and saw a gold knife on the ground and grabbed it and stabbed the red one in the side. It sank in like a hot knife through butter, but I don’t know if it was because of the sharpness of the knife or because of the place I stabbed or what. Then a bright gold light emanated from the wound and the red monster stopped moving entirely. I sat back on the grass, pushing the body away from me while the gold me sat next to me and sighed. Neither of us spoke for several minutes. Then he said “I guess you have questions right?”

7deaae53-e460-41b8-9420-7fa1d09d8e37.text:
I locked eyes with the red hoodie version of me and saw his bloodstained features. Everything from his face to his hands had that red tint and he radiated the smell of it. He made my decision easy. I stayed back and watched him do his work. The red one crept up behind the gold one and snapped his neck. The gold one crumpled. I walked over and watched in morbid fascination as the red one feasted on the gold corpse with sickening speed. After a second or two, he tossed a chunk to me and said the first word I ever heard him say.

“Hungry?”

a927d0b3-cba2-4aff-b493-9f1ce5bc8f51.text:
Any me that got the text would see I texted and assumedly trust me, right? I trust myself, at least. Maybe if nothing else, curiosity would bring them there. Then I could explain what had been happening, what I’ve seen, what I know, and we can form an army of sorts and hunt down these Vacks. Ideally, we find more people like Blake and hunt together.

Or maybe the Vack would get the text. Hey, free food, come to the bridge. I know how to take one down, I think. If I see it, I won’t hesitate.

I had to be smart about how I went about this. I couldn’t show up and wait to be ambushed, but if I got there soon enough, I could do the ambushing. I quickened my pace and made it to the bridge. Within eyesight was a park. Any version of me would probably go there instead, I mean I’m going there, and I’m me. By the time I got there, the sun was setting. My hoodie and knife made me a big target. If the vack saw me, or when I guess, it would do all the work for me.

As I waited, I saw a familiar face up near the bridge. It was the McDonald’s me, in the white hoodie. He was staring directly at me. I ran up to him and felt a terror pulse through my veins. I heard something running behind me, or maybe somethings? It was more than one set of footsteps, but I couldn’t hear exactly how many. Once I got to the white hoodie me, McDonald Me, I pulled my knife and looked in his eyes. He looked in mine and then threw a punch over my shoulder, right into the jaw of the Vack.

I tossed my knife to him and tackled the Vack, keeping it distracted. I fought haphazardly and let myself get pinned to the ground, though I had to keep its teeth far from me. When I was in position, I shouted ”Now!” to McDonald’s me and he stabbed the Vack as though it was planned. The Vack shrieked and went limp above me. I tossed the body aside and sat up on the grass. After a long silence, I took a deep breath and asked a question.

“I guess you have questions right?”

47c7d3c8-33cd-4771-9976-2ed29e3b735b.text:
It would be rude to turn down the invitation, right? I looked around, found which direction the bridge was, and took off. I ran at a speed I never reached before, but I still didn’t feel like I was at my peak yet. I dropped to all fours and raced there. I made it faster than any car could take me, even if it wasn’t a big city in rush hour. I didn’t even feel tired, I hardly broke a sweat. I reached the bridge with the sun still in the sky.

Time to test myself I guess. I walked up to the bridge, and started climbing the suspensions. My hands weren’t slick from all the blood, which was nice but unexplained. Maybe fast drying hands came with my senses? Or maybe I could adjust for the slickness in climbing and they just felt dry? Whatever it was granted me great ease in climbing. I got to the top and watched the sun fall a bit while I watched for any familiar face.

From up here, I could see a lot of the city. I could see people walking all around the streets, I could see faces of the people in cars, I could read their lips on the phone. One woman was calling about dinner and, from here, I could see the restaurant she was calling. I could see all of this at once and not have to focus on any of it. Until, that is, I saw me.

There I was, in a horrid yellow hoodie, crossing the street, headed to the park, it looked like. I jumped. I didn’t hesitate or fear the fall or impact of the bay below me. I knew the pain I would feel, and it didn’t scare me. I plunged into the water and swam to the shore. From there, I ran to the park and beat the yellow hoodie there.

I moved quietly around to intercept his path and waited in ambush. Before he got to my position, he stopped and looked behind him. I followed his gaze and saw me again, but in a white hoodie. He and I locked eyes and I knew what to do. I knew more than I ever had before. I crept up to the yellow hoodie me and snapped his neck in an instant. Then I started eating.

The white hoodie me had approached my meal and I threw a chunk of meat at him. I think it may have been the heart, but I didn’t care enough to check. I just knew I had to say one thing before anything else.

“Hungry?”

1b3aaf3c-e11f-406f-87be-b10dbfdc146b.text: Remember the title of the page you just came from and start with that option in the next game. Until then, play again, or go back to specific parts from here

122b783b-3575-4239-9dd2-5360198fdb24.text: It had been a long time since I went to San Francisco. Long enough to forget what the layout of the streets was, long enough to forget the sight of the Golden Gate Bridge, long enough to forget the details you don’t bother remembering. I thought revisiting the city might be a lot of fun since every memory I had of it was positive. I had plans to visit a friend there first, but when I got there, no one was answering the door and my friend seemed to be avoiding their phone and all of social media in general. So instead I went to the public transit system and got a B.A.R.T. card and went to my new first destination.

31b9f3a7-886d-44ad-8521-4be7021ddc24.text: I got up to follow Blake but my knees were too shaky to stand at all. I heard Blake call out, “Don’t bother until you’re ready! No rush!” then I heard footsteps walking away. I decided to check out the scene.
